article.headline: Shock drop Liberty for eighth straight win
article.linkText: Shock win eighth straight in rough one over NY
article.story:
NEW YORK (AP) -- The Detroit Shock matched the New York Liberty push for push and elbow for elbow, leaving the defending Eastern Conference champions banged and bruised. "I mean, that's one part of our game. Look at our coach -- we're a physical team," forward Swin Cash said of Bill Laimbeer, a former Bad Boy with the Detroit Pistons. "He's never going to let us be a tentative team. We're always going to be an aggressive team." Deanna Nolan scored 20 points to lead the Shock to their eighth straight win with a 75-69 victory over the Liberty on Friday night. After the game, New York learned it would be without leading scorer Becky Hammon for the rest of the season after the guard tore the anterior cruciate ligament in her right knee in the first half. "This is an incredibly bad break for a person who is having an all-star year and who worked so hard in the offseason to become one of the team's best players," New York coach Richie Adubato said. Cash added 17 points and Cheryl Ford had 12 points and seven rebounds for the Shock, who lead the Eastern Conference at 8-1 and are unbeaten since losing to Charlotte to open the season on May 31. The Shock beat the Liberty for the second time in a week after winning 88-83 last Friday. "They have what we want, and that's the Eastern Conference championship," Cash said. "To win some games from New York, and to come into Madison Square Garden and do it, is big for us." Elena Baranova set season highs with 20 points and 10 rebounds for the Liberty, and Tari Phillips added 18 points and 11 rebounds before fouling out with 57 seconds left. "The way the physical play was -- look at me," Phillips said, with ice wrapped around both knees and an ankle. "They were really physical tonight, but I think we matched them. It was unfortunate, because the momentum was shifting to us a couple of times." But losing Hammon, who came in averaging 16.2 points, hurt the Liberty's flow. The fifth-year guard entered with 14:55 left in the first half, and quickly grabbed a rebound and started up the court. She stopped and planted her right foot at the Liberty's 3-point line, then fell and clutched her right knee. She was helped off the court by Tamika Whitmore and a trainer. She was taken to Beth Israel Medical Center for an MRI exam, which revealed the injury. "I know she'll persevere and rehab the knee and come back stronger and better," Adubato said. "She's a warrior," teammate Vickie Johnson said. The Liberty hung tough after Hammon's injury, taking a brief lead in the first half behind Baranova's hustle and 3-point shooting. Point guard Teresa Weatherspoon, who has seen fewer minutes with the emergence of Hammon, had nine points and four assists and was effective down the stretch, but New York could only get within six before having to foul. "That's our goal in the East. They are the champions, and we can learn from a team like them," Laimbeer said. "We can bang with the best of them. "That's what New York has been winning the conference with every year. That's why I modeled our team after them, because when it comes to playoff time, it's about interior scoring and interior defense. That's why I went out and got the players I did." The teams played heated, physical defense the whole game. Vickie Johnson nearly got hurt in the second half chasing an offensive rebound, and Cash was fouled hard by Whitmore, who was called for an offensive foul. Ford, the daughter of Utah Jazz forward Karl Malone, was even whistled for a technical foul after throwing an elbow in the final minutes. "They like to bang down there pretty good," Ford said with her very familiar smile. "We aren't scared. We are going to go out and play our team regardless of who we are playing. We're not going to be scared of them."

Game notes
Liberty F Crystal Robinson missed the game after turning her ankle in practice Thursday. She's day-to-day. Lindsey Yamasaki made the first start of her career in Robinson's place. ... Whitmore started after missing the Liberty's 70-64 win over Phoenix on Wednesday. She sprained her right foot against Charlotte June 22. ... Two of the New York Knicks' draft picks, Maciej Lampe and Slavko Vranes, sat courtside.
